SUMMARY:Africa Fest 2026!
DESCRIPTION:HLS faculty\, students and members of the community will high
 light the five regions of the world's second largest content through enga
 ging activities\, food and drinks of the regions\, mini-language lessons\
 , music and more. Drop in anytime between 11 am and 4:00 pm to the lounge
  and atrium of the Hamilton Lugar School. Then\, from 5-6:30pm\, join us 
 for a fashion show and performances by IU students in the African languag
 es program followed by a communal meal.Africa is NOT what you think! Did 
 you know that in our students'/children's lifetimes Africans will be the 
 majority population on Earth? That African countries have been developing
  faster than China did over the past 30 years? That for more than two dec
 ades\, African countries have dominated the fastest growing economies in 
 the world? That Africans are the most educated immigrant population in th
 e US? That the UN has stated the African continent\, with the youngest po
 pulation on earth\, is also the continent with the most potential for eco
 nomic\, technological\, and innovational growth? There is so much to lear
 n about this continent!&#160\;  Families: enjoy fun\, interactive\, educa
 tional activities!  IU Students: learn the critical reasons why YOU shoul
 d know about the centrality of Africa in the world today\, why you should
  have knowledge about Africa for your future careers - be they in cyberse
 curity\, business\, economics\, social work\, politics\, public health\, 
 international relations\, the arts\, and many other areas!  K-16 Educator
 s: receive information on why and how to incorporate Africa-focused curri
 cular elements\, including funded opportunities!  Parking is available in
  the East Garage on Eagleson\, as well as in the IMU parking lot.This eve
 nt is sponsored by the IU African Studies Program.
X-ALT-DESC;FMTTYPE=text/html:<p>  HLS faculty\, students and members of t
 he community will highlight the five regions of the world's second larges
 t content through engaging activities\, food and drinks of the regions\, 
 mini-language lessons\, music and more. Drop in anytime between 11 am and
  4:00 pm to the lounge and atrium of the Hamilton Lugar School. Then\, fr
 om 5-6:30pm\, join us for a fashion show and performances by IU students 
 in the African languages program followed by a communal meal.</p><p><em>A
 frica is NOT what you think!</em> Did you know that in our students'/chil
 dren's lifetimes Africans will be the majority population on Earth? That 
 African countries have been developing faster than China did over the pas
 t 30 years? That for more than two decades\, African countries have domin
 ated the fastest growing economies in the world? That Africans are the mo
 st educated immigrant population in the US? That the UN has stated the Af
 rican continent\, with the youngest population on earth\, is also the con
 tinent with the most potential for economic\, technological\, and innovat
 ional growth? <em>There is so much to learn about this continent!&#160\;<
 /em></p><p>  Families: enjoy fun\, interactive\, educational activities!<
 /p><p>  IU Students: learn the critical reasons why YOU should know about
  the centrality of Africa in the world today\, why you should have knowle
 dge about Africa for your future careers - be they in cybersecurity\, bus
 iness\, economics\, social work\, politics\, public health\, internationa
 l relations\, the arts\, and many other areas!</p><p>  K-16 Educators: re
 ceive information on why and how to incorporate Africa-focused curricular
  elements\, including funded opportunities!</p><p>  Parking is available 
 in the East Garage on Eagleson\, as well as in the IMU parking lot.</p><p
 ><em>This event is sponsored by the IU African Studies Program.</em></p>
