SUMMARY:EASC Colloquium: How to Read Jinpingmei: Fiction Commentary from 
 the Perspective of Book History and the History of Reading
DESCRIPTION:How did the readers of the late Ming and early Qing cope with
  Jinpingmei\, a 100 chapter-long novel unprecedented in both its content 
 and narrative mode? This talk focuses on Zhang Zhupo's "Jinpingmei dufa" 
 (How to read Jinpingmei) as a way of exploring a wide range of issues con
 cerning fiction commentary of the time. Rather than treating Zhang's "duf
 a" as a historical document that reflects how Jin Ping Mei was actually r
 ead\, or as an indigenous source for constructing a theory of the Chinese
  novel\, I interpret it as an unfinished project aimed at transforming xi
 aoshuo (fiction) into what is called wen or wenzhangŌĆöa broadly defined 
 term that refers to a variety of prose forms and genres at the center of 
 the literati writing tradition. This talk further examines the functions 
 of Zhang Zhupo's para-texts in regulating the reading of Jinpingmei from 
 the perspective of book history and the history of reading.Professor Wei 
 Shang specializes in pre-modern Chinese literature and culture\, especial
 ly the fiction and drama of the Ming and Qing dynasties. His research int
 erests also include print culture\, book history and intellectual history
  of the same period. His book "Rulin Waishi" and Cultural Transformation 
 in Late Imperial China (2003) addresses the role of Confucian ritualism a
 nd fiction in shaping the intellectual and cultural changes of the eighte
 enth century. His other publications are concerned with Jin Ping Mei Cihu
 a (The Plum in the Golden Vase)\, late Ming culture\, fiction commentary\
 , and medieval poetry\, including Writing on Landmarks: From Yellow Crane
  Tower to Phoenix Pavilion (2020). He is the editor and co-editor of seve
 ral volumes in both English and Chinese\, and a contributor to The Cambri
 dge History of Chinese Literature (2010).
X-ALT-DESC;FMTTYPE=text/html:<p>  How did the readers of the late Ming an
 d early Qing cope with <em>Jinpingmei</em>\, a 100 chapter-long novel unp
 recedented in both its content and narrative mode? This talk focuses on Z
 hang Zhupo's "<em>Jinpingmei</em> dufa" (How to read <em>Jinpingmei</em>)
  as a way of exploring a wide range of issues concerning fiction commenta
 ry of the time. Rather than treating Zhang's "dufa" as a historical docum
 ent that reflects how <em>Jin Ping Mei</em> was actually read\, or as an 
 indigenous source for constructing a theory of the Chinese novel\, I inte
 rpret it as an unfinished project aimed at transforming <em>xiaoshuo</em>
  (fiction) into what is called <em>wen</em> or <em>wenzhang</em>ŌĆöa broa
 dly defined term that refers to a variety of prose forms and genres at th
 e center of the literati writing tradition. This talk further examines th
 e functions of Zhang Zhupo's para-texts in regulating the reading of <em>
 Jinpingmei</em> from the perspective of book history and the history of r
 eading.</p><p><span data-teams="true">Professor Wei Shang specializes in 
 pre-modern Chinese literature and culture\, especially the fiction and dr
 ama of the Ming and Qing dynasties. His research interests also include p
 rint culture\, book history and intellectual history of the same period. 
 His book <i>"Rulin Waishi" and Cultural Transformation in Late Imperial C
 hina</i> (2003) addresses the role of Confucian ritualism and fiction in 
 shaping the intellectual and cultural changes of the eighteenth century. 
 His other publications are concerned with <i>Jin Ping Mei Cihua</i> (<i>T
 he Plum in the Golden Vase</i>)\, late Ming culture\, fiction commentary\
 , and medieval poetry\, including <i>Writing on Landmarks: From Yellow Cr
 ane Tower to Phoenix Pavilion</i> (2020). He is the editor and co-editor 
 of several volumes in both English and Chinese\, and a contributor to <i>
 The Cambridge History of Chinese Literature</i> (2010).</span></p>
