LOCATION:GLOBAL &amp\; INTERNATIONAL STUDIES BUILDING - Room Number: 2134
GEO:39.170002;-86.517492
SUMMARY:Taiwan Studies Initiative Spring Book Talk Series - "New Immigran
 ts and Multilingual Linguistic Landscape in Taiwan"
DESCRIPTION:New Immigrants and Multilingual Linguistic Landscape in Taiwa
 n by Ching-Yu Na and Seraf├Łn M. Coronel-Molina explores how migration re
 shapes language use and public signage in Taiwan. Through ethnographic an
 d geosemiotic perspectives\, the book examines multilingual practices\, i
 dentity\, and social inclusion\, highlighting the linguistic presence and
  contributions of new immigrant communities within Taiwan's evolving soci
 olinguistic landscape.Ching-Yu Na is an English teacher and curriculum co
 ordinator at a public elementary school in Taoyuan City\, Taiwan\, and ha
 s also taught at the university level. Her research interests include soc
 iolinguistics\, ethnographic and geosemiotic perspectives on multilingual
  linguistic landscapes\, TESOL\, and World Englishes.Seraf├Łn M. Coronel-
 Molina is Professor in the Literacy\, Culture\, and Language Education an
 d International and Comparative Education programs in the Department of C
 urriculum and Instruction at the School of Education. His research focuse
 s on sociolinguistics\, language policy\, planning\, and revitalization\,
  as well as ethnographic and geosemiotic approaches to multilingual lingu
 istic landscapes\, and translingual and translanguaging practices in educ
 ation.
X-ALT-DESC;FMTTYPE=text/html:<p><em>New Immigrants and Multilingual Lingu
 istic Landscape in Taiwan</em> by Ching-Yu Na and Seraf├Łn M. Coronel-Mol
 ina explores how migration reshapes language use and public signage in Ta
 iwan. Through ethnographic and geosemiotic perspectives\, the book examin
 es multilingual practices\, identity\, and social inclusion\, highlightin
 g the linguistic presence and contributions of new immigrant communities 
 within Taiwan's evolving sociolinguistic landscape.</p><p><strong>Ching-Y
 u Na</strong> is an English teacher and curriculum coordinator at a publi
 c elementary school in Taoyuan City\, Taiwan\, and has also taught at the
  university level. Her research interests include sociolinguistics\, ethn
 ographic and geosemiotic perspectives on multilingual linguistic landscap
 es\, TESOL\, and World Englishes.</p><p><strong>Seraf├Łn M. Coronel-Molin
 a</strong> is Professor in the Literacy\, Culture\, and Language Educatio
 n and International and Comparative Education programs in the Department 
 of Curriculum and Instruction at the School of Education. His research fo
 cuses on sociolinguistics\, language policy\, planning\, and revitalizati
 on\, as well as ethnographic and geosemiotic approaches to multilingual l
 inguistic landscapes\, and translingual and translanguaging practices in 
 education.</p>
